<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1888-06-15T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1888-06-15T00:00:00-05:00" n="215" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d215">
                    <head>No. 215.<lb/><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Bayard</persName>
                            to Mr. <persName type="to">Denby</persName>.</hi></head>
                    <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department
                                    of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1888-06-15"><hi rend="italic">June</hi> 15,
                            1888</date>.</dateline>
                        <seg rendition="#left">No. 329.]</seg></opener>
                    <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I desire to acknowledge the receipt of your
                        No. 639 of the 5th of May last, and to express the Department’s satisfaction
                        that the intricate question relating to the etiquette to be observed between
                        the Chinese foreign office and the diplomatic body at Peking on New Year’s
                        Day has at last been disposed of.</p>
                    <p>I am, sir, etc.,</p>
                    <closer><signed><persName><hi rend="smallcaps">T. F.
                            Bayard.</hi></persName></signed></closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>